Sure — here’s a simple CSS companion that would style those sections cleanly, scale for phones, and preserve high contrast.  

```css
/* Base page setup */
body {
  font-family: "Open Sans", Arial, sans-serif;
  background-color: #f9fafb;
  color: #333;
  line-height: 1.5;
  padding: 1em;
  max-width: 700px;
  margin: auto;
}

/* Section cards */
section {
  border-radius: 0.8em;
  padding: 1.2em;
  margin-bottom: 1em;
}

/* Colored backgrounds for each theme */
.anxiety {
  background: linear-gradient(180deg, #A8E6CE 0%, #DCEDC1 100%);
}

.guilt {
  background: linear-gradient(180deg, #FFF1D0 0%, #FFD8A9 100%);
}

.sadness {
  background: linear-gradient(180deg, #E7E0F8 0%, #D2E0FC 100%);
}

.resources {
  background: linear-gradient(180deg, #FCE0E0 0%, #FFE5EC 100%);
}

/* Text hierarchy */
h1, h2 {
  font-family: "Poppins", sans-serif;
  color: #222;
}

.notice {
  margin-top: 0.4em;
}

.tool {
  font-style: italic;
  margin: 0.6em 0;
}

.next-step {
  font-weight: bold;
}

/* Links and accessibility */
a {
  color: #0073aa;
  text-decoration: underline;
}

a:focus,
a:hover {
  color: #005577;
}

/* Responsive text sizes */
@media (max-width: 480px) {
  body {
    font-size: 16px;
  }
  h2 {
    font-size: 18px;
  }
}

@media (min-width: 481px) {
  body {
    font-size: 17px;
  }
  h2 {
    font-size: 20px;
  }
}

/* Footer disclaimer */
footer {
  font-size: 0.9em;
  color: #666;
  text-align: center;
  margin-top: 2em;
}
```

This sheet keeps everything legible, responsive, and consistent with accessibility guidelines.  
You can attach each emotional block a class such as `class="anxiety"` or `class="guilt"` to automatically apply the correct gradients.  
The footer still provides a clear disclaimer that the material is **educational and not therapy**.

